<subSubSection id="E1FE5EB7BD19D77F63014D0EF86E1EF8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="9573D82819E3FDB17684B3BC44F4897E" pageNumber="17">
Diagnosis: Distinguished from all congeners by the following characters: caudal fin deeply forked; outer, unbranched principal rays of upper and lower lobes longest in each lobe and about equal in length (Littmann et al. 2000, fig. 2); posterior fontanelle elongate, forming conspicuous groove on supraoccipital bone, skin pigmented black in groove; other congeners without elongate posterior fontanelle, supraoccipital groove, or black pigment; unique in having combination of elongate body and broad-shaped head; other 
<taxonomicName id="8062015B0FE3221C4711EA23EE6E13BA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A1B16E22-5503-46E3-8E9E-EF7935778506" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim Cuvier 1829:293" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sorubim</taxonomicName>
species have either elongate body and head, or stout body with broad head.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="21928287E92B8BC6E8E945C979C92D2D" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="BDC7D0037F8B3E8C54EABECC82B8820B" pageNumber="17">
Etymology: the specific epithet cuspi- (from cuspis), Latin for pointed, and -caudus, Latin for tail, refers to the diagnostic pointed caudal-fin lobes. The first part of the English common name “Trans-Andean” describes the general distribution of the fish; the remainder of the name (shovelnose catfish) is familiar to enthusiasts of the aquarium hobby, and differs from that recommended for 
<taxonomicName id="8170C9E9E8DB43E093B7368B4F0F11A5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lima">S. lima</taxonomicName>
(i.e., Duckbill catfish) by Robins et al. (1991).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AA88C109FAAEDA184397FA223417E9DC" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2FAFDE2C6A7D57538E021DBB32D0F4B5" pageNumber="17">
Distribution: 
<taxonomicName id="997328B18F49CCF0E1E68DB4702B84F8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3551D3F9-5069-42B9-AED3-3EA5E8B8A80D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim cuspicaudus Littmann, Burr &amp; Nass 2000:903" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cuspicaudus">Sorubim cuspicaudus</taxonomicName>
occurs west of the Andean Cordillera Oriental, and is endemic to three major drainage basins in northwestern South America: Lago Maracaibo, 
<normalizedToken id="02CEA98009AEB89807A1F2976E3B8EE6" originalValue="Ríos">Rios</normalizedToken>
Magdalena and Sinu (Fig. 10). Miles (1947) reported that 
<taxonomicName id="75D96743D7674FE363ADC4E52B50BA03" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A1B16E22-5503-46E3-8E9E-EF7935778506" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim Cuvier 1829:293" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sorubim</taxonomicName>
(referred to as 
<taxonomicName id="19B13908974D33867CFE2DBB8C13B8F4" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lima">S. lima</taxonomicName>
) was not found in the upper reaches of the 
<normalizedToken id="E694AC2202C5971D1C199142B58A9470" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Cauca in northern Colombia. The cis/trans-Andean distribution pattern exhibited by 
<taxonomicName id="D52B7A70E1A32A8997DADFFC3C19D648" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A1B16E22-5503-46E3-8E9E-EF7935778506" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim Cuvier 1829:293" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sorubim</taxonomicName>
is repeated by some other lowland fish groups that have been critically examined in recent years (see references in Vari (1988) and Harold &amp; Vari (1994).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BE104DEAFD8151DC24F30BDE4C6FC17E" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5E85CE8AD98C78DF3D1A3E4233720475" pageNumber="17">
Remarks: 
<taxonomicName id="375B378733C28F2C72EFABABEA119231" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FC5E6314-9C1D-44D1-BC9E-DC5366AEA176" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim infraoculare Spix 1829:24" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="infraoculare">Sorubim infraoculare Spix and Agassiz 1829</taxonomicName>
was listed as a junior subjective synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="3B10F0E394A4F9D4479122608A178FAF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lima">S. lima</taxonomicName>
above. Eigenmann and Eigenmann (1890) also listed 
<taxonomicName id="8026EA50726287A3D6F1B0D6D0E8824C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FC5E6314-9C1D-44D1-BC9E-DC5366AEA176" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim infraoculare Spix 1829:24" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="infraoculare">S. infraoculare</taxonomicName>
as such in their revision of the South American Nematognathi. Although justification for their conclusion was not included, this well-known revision included one of the first records of 
<taxonomicName id="6CA6B462AC6F34F56FCA00F215392C45" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A1B16E22-5503-46E3-8E9E-EF7935778506" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim Cuvier 1829:293" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sorubim</taxonomicName>
reported from the 
<normalizedToken id="0FD995216498CC196C5B451E54B9C448" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Magdalena drainage, Colombia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
